Tom<br>
Thanks for your concern, I have read our unit diaries and command chronologies as well as our after action reports on many of the operations and incidents we were involved with. I was with the 1st Marine Division and for the most part what those reports indicate are close to what I had written down in the journal I kept. I am still missing some unit reports, it takes months to get a response from the USMC Historical Records section. It took eight months to get a copy of my military medical records.<br>
 <br>
What I am looking for however is the overall VN veteran combat experience. How much of their total time in country was spent in actual combat, sort of what Joe referred to in the Harris study of Vietnam Soldiers above. <br>
Joe mentioned;<br><br>
1/3 of Vietnam soldiers were &quot;heavy combat types&quot;<br>
     My question would be &quot;What does this mean, did they see fight against the NVA was it hand to hand, artillery or heavy fire fights and how long in duration?<br>
1/3 of Vietnam soldiers were &quot;moderate combat types&quot;<br>
      Q. Was it VC or NVA, how large a force did they encounter? etc.<br>
77% of vets saw a American KIA or WIA<br>
      Q. From a fire fight or mortars, bobby traps, mines?<br>
43% killed or thought they killed someone<br>
      Q.. In firefights or by dropping artillery? <br>
23% were wounded<br>
      Q. From incoming mortars, artillery, gun shot wounds, bobby traps etc.<br><br>
Perhaps I just want to know after seeing what you guys here have posted if what I experienced was that much different then the rest of our military units in Vietnam. Was it different then other USMC units such as the 3rd Marine Division? Their combat experiences were almost always NVA engagement, but was it in actual fire fights or under mortar attacks. Guess I'm just wondering out loud.<br><br>
If anyone can steer me in the direction where I can find that info out, I would appreciate it.<br>
Thank you<br>
